subject: HISTORY
text: Show very briefly the historical significance of the following: The coronation of Charlemagne, the mission of St. Columba, the marriage of Henry II of England, the battle of Agincourt, the divorce of Catherine of Aragon, the National Covenant (1638), the Act of Settlement, the Fall of the Bastille, the Indian Mutiny, the Franco-British Entente of (1904).

subject: HISTORY
text: What peoples invaded England between the Saxon Conquest and the reign of Henry II, and with what results? What countries did England invade between the accession of Edward I and the death of Edward III, and with what results?

subject: HISTORY
text: For what reasons may the reign of James IV be regarded as an important period in Scottish history, and the reign of Elizabeth be regarded as a glorious period in English history?

subject: HISTORY
text: What changes in national policy followed the deaths of any two of the following: Edward VI, Oliver Cromwell, Queen Anne, Louis XIV?

subject: HISTORY
text: Give some account of one of the following: The effects of the Treaty of Paris (1763) and of the Treaty of Versailles (1783) upon the development of the British Empire, the importance of sea-power in the Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars, the struggle for the Reform Act of (1832), the causes of the wealth of Great Britain in the 19th century.

subject: HISTORY
text: Trace the careers of any two of the following: Canning, Palmerston, Disraeli, Cardinal Newman, Thomas Chalmers, Cavour, General Botha.

subject: HISTORY
text: Illustrate from the history of Canada and Australia the development of the British Colonies into the British self-governing Dominions.

subject: HISTORY
text: How far is it true to say that, since the close of the Great War, the theory of representative government and democratic institutions has been abandoned on the Continent of Europe?
